Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco—On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a Third World War that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a lengthy meeting on February 4—the day that marked the beginning of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two leaders released a carefully drafted 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is more powerful than any treaty and certainly required careful negotiations in advance.
I was shocked that Xi seemed to fully entrust Putin with the invasion and the war in Ukraine.
He believed that confirming himself as China's lifelong ruler in the second half of this year was merely a formality, and he was certainly confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his lifelong dream in an unbelievable brutal manner.
Putin, nearly 70 years old, feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it has to be now or it will never happen.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar they can blindly follow.
This system is the exact opposite of a democratic society, and this vision has distorted the "soul" of the emotionally sensitive Russian people to an overly sentimental extent.
As a child, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political charity work.
Initially, I established a foundation in my homeland Hungary, and later, I actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also established foundations in Russia, and later in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation there (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly before the massacre at Tiananmen Square erupted).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have closely followed his rise to power and fully understand his ruthless personality.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but he seems to have changed recently.
It seems he has lost touch with reality, as he has formed a fixed notion.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He had believed that Russian-speaking Ukrainians would open their arms to welcome Russian soldiers, but it proved that they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Faced with what seemed to be an overwhelming possibility, the Ukrainian people still carried out an incredible act of resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kyiv is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not without historical basis.
But in the second part of his argument, it is Putin who is misled.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The 2014 events made him very angry.
But Russian troops performed poorly when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers.
The deeply entrenched corruption in the Ministry of Defense when awarding contracts also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But Putin did not blame himself; instead, he seemed to have gone mad.
He has already decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seem to be entirely unchecked.
He committed the entire Russian army to battle and ignored all rules of engagement, particularly indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid, which supplies electricity to the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian forces), was also destroyed.
In besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have had no water or food for nearly a week.
Russia is very likely to lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are both sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, while also attempting to purchase Russian-made MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has created a miracle in strengthening Europe's resolve and unity.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has been unfaithful.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi asserted that Sino-Russian friendship remains "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to exercise the utmost restraint in the war.
It remains fundamentally uncertain whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be ousted before they destroy our civilization.
